result.execSummary:
This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

2:31 PM Prosecuting attorney Mary M Sowinski Ms. appeared in court for the State of Wisconsin, Defendant Terry A. Kemp appeared in court, Attorney Elizabeth F Svehlek appeared in court for Terry A. Kemp. Calling 21CF343 & 22CF15. Svehlek states will waive preliminary hearing in 22CF15 - will proceed with preliminary hearing in 21CF343.  Defendant waives preliminary hearing. Waiver free and voluntary. Court finds that probable cause exists and binds over. State calls Oneida County Patrol Sergeant Nancy Reklau/sworn/direct by Sowinski/witness identifies Defendant/cross by Svehlek/witness is excused. Svehlek/Sowinski statement to probable cause. Court statement to charges - believes more testimony is necessary - Sowinski will refile. Svehlek does not want new date today will start from scratch. Svehlek states will except service. Sowinski moves to continue and adjourn preliminary hearing. Svehlek objects - because evidence is closed. Sowinski states Information will be filed that mirrors Complaint in 20CF15. Sowinski willing to proceed to Arraignment today; waives further reading and enters not guilty pleas. Bond continued in 22CF15. adj. 03:02 PM
Pre-trial conference scheduled for March 8, 2022 at 02:00 pm.
